│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SimplifyIndVar.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.             │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe indvars pass is replacing the comparison icmp   │
│ eq i32 %phi, 0 with a constant false at b1, which changes control flow and    │
│ produces an incorrect result. The original program returns 5, while the       │
│ transformed target returns 7. The replacement is driven by                    │
│ SimplifyIndvar::eliminateIVComparison using                                   │
│ ScalarEvolution::evaluatePredicateAt to claim the comparison is invariant and │
│ constant in the loop context.\n\nThe IR contains an unsigned divide by zero:  │
│ %udiv6 = udiv i32 %phi2, 0 inside the loop, which is undefined behavior and   │
│ results in poison per the LLVM LangRef. %phi depends on %udiv6 along the      │
│ backedge, and SCEV builds SCEVUDivExpr expressions with a divisor 0. Such     │
│ SCEVs should be treated as containing undef/poison. Using these to prove      │
│ constants is unsound and can lead to incorrect simplifications.\n\n2.         │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\n- SCEV forms in the log:\n  %phi -->                    │
│ ({0,+,1}<nuw><nsw><%b1> /u 0) U: empty-set S: empty-set\n  %udiv6 -->         │
│ ({1,+,1}<nuw><nsw><%b1> /u 0) U: empty-set S: empty-set\nThis shows SCEV      │
│ created UDiv expressions with a zero denominator, and their ranges are        │
│ empty-set, which is not a well-defined numeric value and indicates the        │
│ presence of undef.\n- ScalarEvolution \"Determining loop execution counts\"   │
│ concludes loop %b1 has a constant max backedge-taken count of 0, and indvars  │
│ prints \"Eliminated comparison\" for %icmp. The transformed IR sets the       │
│ branch in b1 to \"false\", folding away the %phi == 0 check, and similarly b3 │
│ to \"true\".\n- Alive2 verification demonstrates a mismatch: the source can   │
│ reach b7 and return 5; the target forces b8 returning 7.\n\n3. Root Cause     │
│ Analysis:\nSimplifyIndvar::eliminateIVComparison calls                        │
│ evaluatePredicateAt(Pred, S, X, CtxI) with S and X being SCEVs derived from   │
│ the ICmp operands in the loop's scope. In this case, S is a SCEVUDivExpr with │
│ a zero divisor, i.e., it semantically contains undef/poison. Using such SCEVs │
│ to evaluate predicates is unsound: any reasoning predicated on values that    │
│ may be poison or undefined should not lead to replacing comparisons with      │
│ constants unless the predicate is provably independent of the undef. The      │
│ current code lacks a guard against SCEVs containing undef, so                 │
│ evaluatePredicateAt returns a value and the pass replaces the comparison with │
│ a constant, leading to wrong-code.\n\nThis is consistent with existing        │
│ protections elsewhere: multiple users of ScalarEvolution check                │
│ SE.containsUndefs(S) before leveraging SCEV facts (e.g., LoopStrengthReduce,  │
│ Delinearization). SimplifyIndVar should similarly avoid folding when either   │
│ operand contains undef.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should add a        │
│ conservative guard in SimplifyIndvar::eliminateIVComparison to bail out of    │
│ constant-folding the comparison when either S or X contains undef in the      │
│ given scope. Specifically, after computing S and X but before calling         │
│ evaluatePredicateAt, insert:\n- A check: if (SE->containsUndefs(S) ||         │
│ SE->containsUndefs(X)) return; This prevents eliminating comparisons based on │
│ undefined SCEVs.\n\nEdit point details:\nFile:                                │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SimplifyIndVar.cpp\nLines: 267-276\nChange: Insert  │
│ a guard after computing S and X and before building                           │
│ Users/CtxI/evaluatePredicateAt. For example:\n\n  // If either operand's SCEV │
│ contains undef/poison (e.g. udiv by zero),\n  // we cannot soundly evaluate   │
│ the predicate to a constant.\n  if (SE->containsUndefs(S) ||                  │
│ SE->containsUndefs(X))\n    return;\n\nThis keeps the rest of the logic       │
│ unchanged but prevents the unsound constant replacement in the presence of    │
│ undef.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy adding a containsUndefs guard before             │
│ evaluatePredicateAt in eliminateIVComparison, we prevent indvars from folding │
│ comparisons that depend on undefined SCEV expressions (like udiv by 0). This  │
│ avoids the incorrect transformation observed in the reproducer, preserves     │
│ correct control flow, and aligns with how other passes handle SCEVs with      │
│ undef. The expected effect is that indvars will no longer print \"Eliminated  │
│ comparison\" for the %phi == 0 in this case, and the target will match the    │
│ source behavior."})                                                           │
